===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|was}}, from {{inh|en|ang|wæs}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*was}}, (compare {{cog|sco|was}}, {{cog|fy|was}} (dated, ''wie'' is generally preferred today), {{cog|nl|was}}, {{cog|nds|was}}, {{cog|de|war}}, {{cog|sv|var}}), from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂wes-||to reside}}, whence also {{m|en|vestal}}. The paradigm of “to be” has been since the time of Proto-Germanic a synthesis of three originally distinct verb stems. The infinitive form {{m|en|be}} is from Proto-Indo-European {{m|ine-pro|*bʰuH-||to become}}. The forms {{m|en|is}} and {{m|en|are}} are both derived from Proto-Indo-European {{m|ine-pro|*h₁es-||to be}}. Lastly, the past forms starting with ''w-'' such as ''was'' and {{m|en|were}} are from Proto-Indo-European {{m|ine-pro|*h₂wes-||to reside}}.

